<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0049EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-NorthCarolinaAt-A-Glance     03-08 0333</FIRST><SECOND>BC-North Carolina At-A-Glance,340</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from North Carolina to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 82   Super delegates: 7   Total: 89   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, May 21 and Saturday, June 18   North Carolina Democrats pick 82 pledged national conventiondelegates through a ``bonus delegate'' primary system.   The presidential candidate receiving the most votes in acongressional district in the March 8 primary will receive onedelegate from that district, and the remainder of the pledgeddelegates from that district will be allocated among thepresidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary.   North Carolina's remaining 29 pledged national conventiondelegates will be allocated among presidential candidates inproportion to the results of the primary.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 54   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Friday, April 1 and Saturday, June 4   All of North Carolina's 54 Republican National Conventiondelegates are allocated among presidential candidates in proportionto the results of the March 8 primary.   A presidential candidate must receive at least 10 percent of thevote statewide to qualify for any national convention delegates.   Thirty-three people to serve as delegates from congressionaldistricts are chosen at district conventions held during April.   The remaining 21 delegates at-large are picked at the stateconvention June 3-4.   The delegates are not required to pledge their support to apresidential candidate.   While the state's delegation is required to vote in line withthe primary results, this obligation applies only to the firstballot, and the actual preferences of individual delegates maydiffer from the way the delegation as a whole must vote.</TEXT></DOC>